Windows is one of the most widely used operating systems in homes, businesses, and government organizations. It provides a graphical user interface (GUI) that allows users to interact with files, applications, and system settings.
Because of its popularity, Windows is a common target for cyberattacks.

Key Components:

Desktop
The main workspace where users access applications, files, and shortcuts.

File Explorer
Used to navigate, organize, and manage files and folders.

Task Manager
Displays running processes, system performance, and resource usage.

Useful for:

Monitoring applications
Identifying suspicious processes
Troubleshooting performance issues

Control Panel / Settings
Used to configure system settings, devices, accounts, and security options.

User Accounts
Windows uses user accounts to control access to the system.

Common account types:

Standard User
Limited permissions for everyday tasks.

Administrator
Full control over the system and its settings.

Following the principle of least privilege, users should only have the access they need.

File System
Windows commonly uses the NTFS (New Technology File System).

Features include:

File permissions
Encryption support
Access control

Windows Security Features

Common security controls include:

Windows Defender
Windows Firewall
User Account Control (UAC)
Automatic updates

These features help protect systems from malware and unauthorized access.

Why important in cybersecurity:

Windows systems are frequently targeted by attackers, making it important to understand:

User permissions
Running processes
File locations
Security settings

Many cybersecurity investigations and enterprise environments involve Windows systems.

Key Takeaways:
Windows is one of the most widely used operating systems.
File Explorer, Task Manager, and Settings are key administrative tools.
User accounts and permissions help control access.
Built-in security features help protect the system.
Understanding Windows is essential for cybersecurity professionals.
